07524nam a22008895i 9780812295092DE-B159720180924034856.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||180924s2018    pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808122950927 a10.9783/97808122950922doi  a(DE-B1597)497592  a(OCoLC)1030536881  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aHIS0370102bisacsh 7aHIS0370202bisacsh04a809/.93356122300aBlood Matters :bStudies in European Literature and Thought, 1400-1700 /cBonnie Lander Johnson, Eleanor Decamp. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource :b10 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction / rLander Johnson, Bonnie / Decamp, Eleanor -- tPart I Circulation -- tChapter 1. Was the Heart "Dethroned"? Harvey's Discoveries and the Politics of Blood, Heart, and Circulation / rHealy, Margaret -- tChapter 2. "The Lake of my Heart" Blood, Containment, and the Boundaries of the Person in the Writing of Dante and Catherine of Siena / rWebb, Heather -- tChapter 3. Sorting Pistol's Blood Social Class and the Circulation of Character in Shakespeare's 2 Henry IV and Henry V / rCraik, Katharine A. -- tPart II Wounds -- tChapter 4. Mantled in Blood Shakespeare's Bloodstains and Early Modern Textile Culture / rLees-Jeffries, Hester -- tChapter 5. Rethinking Nosebleeds Gendering Spontaneous Bleedings in Medieval and Early Modern Medicine / rZuccolin, Gabriella / King, Helen -- tChapter 6. Screaming Bleeding Trees Textual Wounding and the Epic Tradition / rMoshenska, Joe -- tPart III Corruption -- tChapter 7. Corruption, Generation, and the Problem of Menstrua in Early Modern Alchemy / rNummedal, Tara -- tChapter 8. Bloody Students Youth, Corruption, and Discipline in the Medieval Classroom / rParsons, Ben -- tChapter 9. Blood, Milk, Poison Romeo and Juliet's Tragedy of "Green" Desire and Corrupted Blood / rLander Johnson, Bonnie -- tPart IV Proof -- tChapter 10. "In Every Wound There is a Bloody Tongue". Cruentation in Early Modern Literature and Psychology / rDawson, Lesel -- tChapter 11. "In such abundance . . . that it fill a Bason". Early Modern Bleeding Bowls / rDecamp, Eleanor -- tChapter 12. Macbeth and the Croxton Play of the Sacrament: Blood and Belief in Early English Stagecraft / rDutton, Elisabeth -- tChapter 13. Simular Proof, Tragicomic Turns, and Cymbeline's Bloody Cloth / rParker, Patricia -- tPart V Signs and Substance -- tChapter 14. Blood of the Grape / rDolan, Frances E. -- tChapter 15. Blood on the Butcher's Knife: Images of Pig Slaughter in Late Medieval Illustrated Calendars / rJørgensen, Dolly -- tChapter 16. Queer Blood / rBarr, Helen -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments  aIn late medieval and early modern Europe, definitions of blood in medical writing were slippery and changeable: blood was at once the red fluid in human veins, a humor, a substance governing crucial Galenic models of bodily change, a waste product, a cause of corruption, a source of life, a medical cure, a serum appearing under the guise of all other bodily secretions, and-after William Harvey's discovery of its circulation-the cause of one of the greatest medical controversies of the premodern period. Figurative uses of "blood" are even more difficult to pin down. The term appeared in almost every sphere of life and thought, running through political, theological, and familial discourses.Blood Matters explores blood as a distinct category of inquiry and draws together scholars who might not otherwise be in conversation. Theatrical and medical practice are found to converge in their approaches to the regulation of blood as a source of identity and truth; medieval civic life intersects with seventeenth-century science and philosophy; the concepts of class, race, gender, and sexuality find in the language of blood as many mechanisms for differentiation as for homogeneity; and fields as disparate as pedagogical theory, alchemy, phlebotomy, wet-nursing, and wine production emerge as historically and intellectually analogous. The volume's essays are organized within categories derived from medieval and early modern understanding of blood behaviors-Circulation, Wounds, Corruption, Proof, and Signs and Substances-thereby providing the terms through which interdisciplinary and cross-period conversations can take place.Contributors: Helen Barr, Katharine Craik, Lesel Dawson, Eleanor Decamp, Frances E. Dolan, Elisabeth Dutton, Margaret Healy, Dolly Jørgensen, Helen King, Bonnie Lander Johnson, Hester Lees-Jeffries, Joe Moshenska, Tara Nummedal, Patricia Parker, Ben Parsons, Heather Webb, Gabriella Zuccolin.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Sep 2018) 4aCultural Studies. 4aEuropean History. 4aHistory. 4aLiterature. 4aMedieval and Renaissance Studies. 4aWorld History.1 aDecamp, Eleanor, eeditor.1 aLander Johnson, Bonnie, eeditor.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018 Englishz978311060425208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018z9783110603255oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2018 Englishz978311060403008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2018z9783110603149oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook package 2017-2019z978311065989408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniv.of Pennsylvania Press eBook-Package 2017-2018z978311065747008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniv.of Pennsylvania Press eBook-Package 2018z978311060663840uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/9780812295092423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780812295092.jpg